        "discussion_id": "2048423091",
        "commented_code": "@@ -0,0 +1,27 @@\n+{\n+  \"name\": \"@mermaid-js/examples\",\n+  \"version\": \"0.0.1\",\n+  \"description\": \"Mermaid examples package\",\n+  \"author\": \"Sidharth Vinod\",\n+  \"type\": \"module\",\n+  \"module\": \"./dist/mermaid-examples.core.mjs\",\n+  \"types\": \"./dist/mermaid.d.ts\",\n+  \"exports\": {\n+    \".\": {\n+      \"types\": \"./dist/index.d.ts\",\n+      \"import\": \"./dist/mermaid-examples.core.mjs\",\n+      \"default\": \"./dist/mermaid-examples.core.mjs\"\n+    },\n+    \"./*\": \"./*\"\n+  },\n+  \"files\": [\n+    \"dist\"\n+  ],\n+  \"scripts\": {\n+    \"clean\": \"rimraf dist\"\n+  },\n+  \"dependencies\": {},\n+  \"devDependencies\": {\n+    \"mermaid\": \"workspace:*\"\n+  }",
        "comment_created_at": "2025-04-20T08:22:42+00:00",
        "comment_author": "sidharthv96",
        "comment_body": "@aloisklink why don't we lock the package versions of `mermaid` & `@mermaid-js/examples`?\r\n\r\nI've done it for the `@mermaid-js/tiny` package in https://github.com/mermaid-js/mermaid/pull/4734, we can use the same approach here as well. \r\n\r\nUnlike `@mermaid-js/tiny`, there will be some unnecessary releases in `@mermaid-js/examples`, but it'll make the UX much easier, as it's clear that the examples for `mermaid@x.y.z` will be in `@mermaid-js/examples@x.y.z`.",
        "pr_file_module": null
      },
      {
        "comment_id": "2053607161",
        "repo_full_name": "mermaid-js/mermaid",
        "pr_number": 6453,
        "pr_file": "packages/examples/package.json",
        "discussion_id": "2048423091",
        "commented_code": "@@ -0,0 +1,27 @@\n+{\n+  \"name\": \"@mermaid-js/examples\",\n+  \"version\": \"0.0.1\",\n+  \"description\": \"Mermaid examples package\",\n+  \"author\": \"Sidharth Vinod\",\n+  \"type\": \"module\",\n+  \"module\": \"./dist/mermaid-examples.core.mjs\",\n+  \"types\": \"./dist/mermaid.d.ts\",\n+  \"exports\": {\n+    \".\": {\n+      \"types\": \"./dist/index.d.ts\",\n+      \"import\": \"./dist/mermaid-examples.core.mjs\",\n+      \"default\": \"./dist/mermaid-examples.core.mjs\"\n+    },\n+    \"./*\": \"./*\"\n+  },\n+  \"files\": [\n+    \"dist\"\n+  ],\n+  \"scripts\": {\n+    \"clean\": \"rimraf dist\"\n+  },\n+  \"dependencies\": {},\n+  \"devDependencies\": {\n+    \"mermaid\": \"workspace:*\"\n+  }",
        "comment_created_at": "2025-04-22T08:27:01+00:00",
        "comment_author": "aloisklink",
        "comment_body": "> @aloisklink why don't we lock the package versions of mermaid & @mermaid-js/examples?\r\n\r\nHmmmm, you mean if you have version `11.7.0` of `mermaid`, you want the `@mermaid-js/examples` version to also be `11.7.0`?\r\n\r\nThe problem is that there wouldn't be a warning if you install `mermaid: \"11.7.0\"` and `@mermaid-js/examples: \"11.8.1-different-version\"`, unless `@mermaid-js/examples` has a `peerDependencies` field on `mermaid`.\r\n\r\nBut each time you make `peerDependencies` stricter, you're supposed to do a major version bump of `@mermaid-js/examples` (and I believe that's what changesets will do for us automatically if we use a `peerDependencies`).\r\n\r\nMaybe we could instead have a `peerDependencies: {mermaid: \"~11.7.0\"}`? If it's the `~` specifier, then we could do patch changes to `mermaid` without bumping `@mermaid-js/examples`, but minor changes would publish a new version, even if it's a no-op?",
        "pr_file_module": null
      }
    ]
  },
